Food is to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, the inflation rate was higher in November than expected - after the 2.6% in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1% was recorded, as reported by the Statistical Office of the EU in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the Leitzins. In its discretion, the interest rate reduction would favor rising commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment to create an inflationary spiral.
The ECB is striving to keep the inflation rate below 2%, or at least close to the 2% mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a state of crisis: one has to “condemn” inflation in order to rule out the need for further action.
At 3.3 per cent, the inflation rate in November reached a 12-year record high in Germany; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the eurozone has been driven by rising food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat listings rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in the price of food oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to decline to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1%.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup locates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while approval for the socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
With partisan voters, the difference is clear thanks to the strong determination of the opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) oppose one-fifth (20 percent) of support for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry barrier: they come up to 2% in the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low, the overall economic mood has further deteriorated - never before has the share of those who judge the country's economic situation as "extremely bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it "pretty bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, the families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only a tenth expects an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents — a historic high — rated the prime minister’s work as “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of respondents have strong or general confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while the share of supporters for Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the leader of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that dissatisfaction with the prime minister can be managed even without a change of government.
After the riots last October, 35% had voted for the remainder of the government and the head of government, today that share is only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent answered that they would “certainly” participate, and another 20 percent would “probably” cast their vote.
By way of comparison: if the parliamentary elections were to be held this Sunday, only 55 percent would "surely" go to the polls, another 15 percent would consider their participation to be "probable".
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% would vote against the hospital day-to-day allowance.
Turned to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty" the proportions of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would be even 81, 84, or 89 percent, respectively.
Even the most expensive, Tesco increased by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade area also maintained this year’s average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no increase in VAT this year.
Articles from Napi Gazdaság
In the Budaörs trade triangle, the price of the usual Christmas basket of the "Napi" has also increased by 16 percent this year, although price increases of over 1,000 HUF have been recorded in all hypermarkets.
After prices in the food markets "galoped" last December, the percentage of the price has not fallen drastically, compared to the already high, earlier baseline level.
