However, the country is reported to have a lower frequency of customers, so many multis complain among the opinion pollsters that they could not even achieve the planned sales, not only in food but also in sustainable consumer goods.
In many places disinfectants are saved
More than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overcrowding of staff - all factors that are not exactly beneficial to the containment of infections, according to the senior doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the János hospital, an MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Since then, an important operation has not been performed due to the bacterium that is still in the patient's body.
By December 10 of this year, 1094 hospitals have reported infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, senior physician at the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, but the dark number is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsil inflammation, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or improperly used, antibiotic-resistant bacteria are produced from the well-responsive bacteria, which under appropriate conditions spread rapidly in hospitals.
Especially in patients with weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the daily routine of the hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are checked for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for curbing the formation or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients admitted and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not as common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance company for this investigation.
Therefore, most cases would only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
On the part of the European Union there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can be formed, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
Among outpatients, or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, according to Karolina Böröcz.
The disinfectants are saved
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to the other by nursing staff.
It is precisely for this reason that hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area as well.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient in the home hospitals.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds lined up close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the financially less well-positioned hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that almost favor the development of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes health insurance huge costs, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
After initial signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made the prevention of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infection in hospitals one of its priorities.
