Another EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements in Budapest on Friday, totalling EUR 400 million. The money is to go to education, transport and environmental infrastructure and the energy industry.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental protection projects implemented with grants from the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement of 100 million was signed earlier, the current agreement dealing with the use of the EUR 200 million granted.
The amount of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement is also to be spent on the budgetary financing of education projects.
The EIB has allocated a total of EUR 300 million to Hungary for this purpose; the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later on in the context of the extension of the credit agreement.
In the area of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will mainly be used in research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
During the meeting, the subway line 4 was also mentioned.
It was agreed that as soon as Hungary has clarified the details of subway financing with the EU, the original contract and any modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects totalling EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest rates are EURIBOR-bound, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, free of provision.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe is looking at the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who still buys the cheapest market in the EU, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly currently the most sought-after pavement for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
Among the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "gold coast", the "sun coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, however, properties around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior will sooner or later also attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favorable area of Russian has more buyers.
The capital city of Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office spaces offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on its best way to become one of Europe’s most attractive golfing paradises, attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons as well in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy property in Bulgaria are also looking for a change in their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are predominantly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down buy either revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or decayed homes for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication options are greatly written, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed in the top ten destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of increasing value in the medium to long term.
However, real estate in the capital is constantly becoming more expensive, due to the ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the last five years there has been an annual price increase of 21 percent.
The price increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are consulting on the Bali roadmap, which sets the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol expires.
A fierce debate is currently underway between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signalled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether the industrialized countries are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on assistance to developing countries has also been reached.
The adjustment fund, which is subject to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be administered by a 16-member Council, which is expected to be part of the UN Global Environmental Facility (GEF), as outlined in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s commitment to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that by 2020, the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (based on 1990 levels), whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be achieved successfully. The Union would even be willing to advocate a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialized countries in the world or developing countries are also willing to do their utmost to meet their commitments in a responsible manner.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the states that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 per cent, while the EU with its then 15 member states had already committed to a decrease of 8%.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the years 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international, with the latest Nobel Peace Prize awarded scientific climate change committee of the UN.
This would delay the emission reduction, and increasing the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2°C would be inevitable, resulting in extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British Army Advertises on YouTube
British army units have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The shots with miniature cameras attached to helmets are checked at the air base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are posted on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under the Defence Headquarters in the spring of 2007 to publish videos of Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the International Peace Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of the foreign operations.
Propaganda of this kind is almost free compared to conventional television ads, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully processed, censored shots, also make it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, at most, the losses are talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, from the sites of war in Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos shot in use have already been uploaded to the platform, but this "genus" has only recently been discovered by the British for themselves.
However, the Americans advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less life-threatening simulation.
