Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have raised the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things: In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk represents "the intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is presumably aimed at provoking such a clash, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "People in public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups, who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition."
It is suspected that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention on the part of the domestic and foreign media, "have seriously damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: Since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has been continuously booming, so that since summer 2007 several organisations called themselves "national self-defense associations" have been established.
"These groups are common in defining themselves as a civil organization, while openly bragging about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (catastrophe protection, national defense, preserving order), citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further: all this is done according to that method which tries to disguise various political aspirations, based on the political and party-disgustingness of the population, as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association are therefore not only used to circumvent legal obstacles that could arise in the course of registration in court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard also represent a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited in several neighbouring countries as a potential source of danger, according to some ultranationalist politicians in certain neighbouring countries, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard is a confirmation of its own anti-Hungarian policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region," he said.
From the research institute’s point of view, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an individual phenomenon in Central-Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
The activities of the Hungarian Guard are reportedly comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced in August 2007 by the BNU.
Against the backdrop of the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard were the Roma mass riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took the incidents as the occasion for the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the goal of the organization was "national protection".
