Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary holidays are regulated by law, so the practice of rearranging working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year gives us fewer such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood by "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and days off from work.
Working days are mostly church holidays, or are related to important historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are days free of work - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve festivities can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The national holidays are March 15, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, the commemoration of the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August the founding of the state, on the 1st of May the work is celebrated, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each for Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "workday postponement" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is ultimately to be worked out, is for many years determined by the Minister of Labour in his own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employers, public servants and civil servants alike.
Except only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on holidays.
Heuer the working order is only confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24 life here remains formally, since most take time balance for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the holidays specifically cancelled for it.
Next year, there will be more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer re-dispositions on working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day so that Friday, May 2 can be a rest day.
The second re-disposition is related to the holiday on October 23rd: On Saturday, October 18th, you will have to work on Friday, October 24th in advance.
However, the end of the year will be completely in the sign of the holidays, after 24 December everything will stand still, even if New Year’s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
