For example, the U.S. Fed is auctioning $40 billion, another 24 making it easy for the European and Swiss central banks.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to prevent or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties in the economy, the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in a report for his clients.
“Central banks’ coordinated action has reduced the likelihood of a US recession from 65% to about 50%,” Baumohl added in his report.
