In addition to growing resistance from the Taliban, the eight participating states are also discussing further co-ordination plans among allies.
While the United States, through its Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, called on NATO units to increase activity, Britain sees priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and in intensifying development aid.
“In Afghanistan, progress is noticeable, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is to enable residents to start economic development and security themselves,” said Des Browne, British Minister of Defense, to the BBC.
Ninety percent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents has reached the highest level in five years, according to the American army.
The number of acts of violence has increased by 27 percent compared to the previous year, in the southern province of Helmand even by sixty percent.
The NATO countries have stationed about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in the southern territory.
