For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was brought before a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been charged in Sudan for insulting Islam, was sentenced to 15 days in prison by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening and subsequently expelled.
The British woman was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old pupils to name a teddy bear Mohammed, despite the fact that any portrayal of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of pupils complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture several times, the 54-year-old elementary school teacher, who worked at Unity High School in Khartoum, was picked up at home on Sunday and charged with insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children suggest eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, school principal Robert Boules reports.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first names.
Surely, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear himself did not wear a sign with that name, but the problem is quite simple that the portrayal of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons’ Muslim colleagues, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said that he knows her well, and she would never have done anything with which she might be too close to a religious faith, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is just an innocent mistake.
An opinion shared by many students of the teacher who describe them as being very attentive to their students and as a person who never speaks about religion in the class.
It should be borne in mind that the first name Mohammed is also the second most commonly given second name in the United Kingdom, for which there are 14 different spellings in English.
This first name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of honor to the Prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
For example, can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
