The White House chief stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian authority under Abbas ultimately seek a peace treaty that will clarify all open issues without exception, including the central issues.
This designation encompasses the three major problems that the disputes between Israelis and Palestinians mainly revolve around: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem, and the fate of the Arab refugees who were expelled from their homeland in the 1948 conflict, which lies in the present-day state of Israel.
After the American president took the floor, Abbas insisted that the upcoming negotiations be conducted comprehensively and thoroughly and provide a settlement for all points, including Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, the water and security.
When Olmert, for his part, took the floor, he pledged that the upcoming ceasefire negotiations should be conducted directly and without interruption and that he would endeavour to end them before the end of 2008.
Bush has set the deadline for the implementation of his vision of two states, one Palestinian and one Israeli, which exist side by side by the end of 2008.
Saudi Arabia has disclosed that it has received an assurance in this sense from Bush before deciding to attend the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a great success for Washington, has set in motion a plan adopted by all Arab countries that offers Israel peace in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
