Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is indispensable for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has achieved several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools crafted by the astronauts to perform the repair.
The problem arose on Wednesday when the astronauts had discharged the Harmony module from the space shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that is expected to soon be accommodated by European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module labs.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was to implement a 17.5-tonne module for power generation via solar panels already on the ISS to bring it to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began restructuring the solar panels of the module, whose span is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be folded up like accordions, was damaged by a clamped cable over a length of about one meter.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to further damage the collector.
The astronauts, who originally left the space shuttle Discovery for a control tour and then repaired another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30-metre-long remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle that had been attached to the station to perform the repair.
He is one of NASA's best spacewalkers.
Large, resilient, very skillful, he has a well-developed torso and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was thus selected to operate the injured solar panel.
After carefully examining the damage, he cut through the faulty cable and attached some sort of rail to the damaged site.
He was assisted by a second spacewalker who remained near the lock, and, inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey club, wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar panels that generate several hundred volts, had been designed and engineered by the astronauts aboard the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited for the collector to be fully unfolded before counting down his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before today seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery, expected to begin their return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
