In parallel with the parliamentary drafting, which ended its meeting today with the congressional decision in the Senate on the supplementary/amendment amendments pertaining to the project, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law, with the intention of allowing the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
Representatives of the various companies unanimously commended the efforts of congress and senators, who in their negotiations and voting had the goal of establishing the best possible regulation that ensures the safety of investors and regulates individual entrepreneurial activities in order to guarantee a generally efficient market event.
In addition to the modernisation of financial markets, the MIFID, which re-enacts the Investment Services Regulation, aims to improve investor protection, increase the control of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new directive enables financial advice to be offered to both specialized companies and natural or legal persons and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services undertakings (ESIS), the consultancy undertakings that merge with securities investment and brokerage firms.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, so that the regulated circulating markets will be added the multilateral systems of the transaction of securities and the systems for the internationalization of trade orders, which would eventually compete with the current economic players.
The law obliges investment companies to disclose the priorities of their company profile, the confrontation and the ways of dealing with risks in the market and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV's control task.
The congressional economic commission subsequently envisaged further changes, with the decision that the securities bond must now be considered a complex financial instrument for the investor due to its high degree of risk, confirmed by the U.S. mortgage and banking crisis.
In addition, the entry into force of the Directive on the legal limitation of areas of work for graduated economists was used; 30 years after the 1977 regulation, which restricted the areas of work reserved for economists, was adopted.
The Senate, for its part, has established new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the economic mediator, who works on an external account, does not require authorization from the CNMV and can offer its services for the commercialization of products and customer acquisition at the same time several investment companies.
The Harmonized Consumer Price Index (CPI) rose five tenths in November to now 4.1%.
The indicator used by Eurostat to assess the inflation rate within the European Union provides the average price development in Spain in November.
Its publication is in line with the principles of Eurostat and the European Central Bank (ECB), which seek to compare local and quality to US products by publishing the data.
The forecast for the indicator can be prepared prematurely by applying the same approach as the harmonised consumer price index, but at the same time using various other statistical modelling methods to estimate the information not available at the time of calculation.
However, the Spanish Statistical Office (INE) cautioned that the indicator prematurely determined only serves as a guideline and therefore does not have to agree with the final result announced on 14 December.
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) will remain at a relatively high level
According to the Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Economics and Finance Pedro Solbes, the increase in the CPI in November is a temporary development; at the same time, it assured that the price index would remain at a relatively high level in the coming months.
Nevertheless, Solbes noted in the halls of the congressional building that even if the current number is not good, Spain’s inflation difference to the other members of the monetary union has remained more or less the same in recent years.
He also stated that there were fewer surprises in November than in the previous month, when the government did not expect such a large increase.
We expected a value of around 4%, the Minister of Economics and Finance announced in light of the forecast released today.
