New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute rages between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe being impaired.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are conducted through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be charged more because the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," Ukraine's economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit charges [to Western Europe] over Ukraine.”
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This resulted in a drop in exports to Western Europe, which drastically pushed prices up.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the supply of the European Union.
Russia has the world’s largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS “must monitor foreign workers”
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the controls of criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of chief financial inspector Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought to Scotland in conjunction with the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish state health service does not have any precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were performed correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The chief financial inspector examined personnel recruited outside the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road vehicle was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared on a video broadcast at the Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bombing in Britain.
The State Health Service is expected to conduct pre-employment checks to ensure that foreign employees have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal record records, the agency does not have the authority to obtain this information outside the UK.
The chief auditor’s report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should pick up guidelines from the criminal record excerpt that helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, they were not routinely performed," the report said.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigative guidelines to a high degree before hiring, but added, “Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information is available about the number of foreign health care workers.”
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was “extremely unlikely” that investigations ahead of hiring potential NHS staff would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
“The report says that current NHS Scotland pre-employment tests work well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide,” he said.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards have problems identifying those employees who are on leave indefinitely.
The investigation further found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian were predominantly followed.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment controls for foreign staff in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “It was my concern to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport.”
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices would be reflected in updated guidelines on pre-employment control investigations by all staff, including those from abroad, whose release is planned next month.
