The climate on Venus could reveal a glimpse of the future of the Earth
Venus was perhaps once a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit show that the planet resembles a remote twin of the Earth even more than previously known.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is somewhat closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, conditions on Venus would have been very similar to those on Earth and could even have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unbridled carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere due to sunlight, and a slower rotational rate, Venus embarked on a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency’s Venus Express space probe, which has been investigating the plant for a year, offer a sobering look at how the Earth could evolve in the face of catastrophic climate changes.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the heads of the Venus Express Mission, said: “It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise pretty similar.”
"Our new data allows us to construct a scenario where Venus started billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment."
