Pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall in; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No noble titles appear to have been sold, no Parisian politician paid hotel bills, no extramarital toes sucked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has concealed donations to the British ruling Labour Party over more than <0xC2><0xA3>650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something that would have done well without the competitive Gordon Brown.
When two months ago the prime minister withdrew the demand for an election, insulting the intelligence of the British in a foolish way by claiming that opinion polls had not influenced this decision, there was hope that he would offer a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly sharp-minded representative chairman of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once dreaded Brown from Stalin has evolved into Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a beaten bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to amend tax laws have raised corporate associations against the government.
The tax authorities’ loss of personal data of 25 million people showed unimaginable administrative punches.
A trio of retired generals started an uprising in the upper house in protest against cuts in military spending: being minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the diverse donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s Secretary General (and her former Chief Executive Officer) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown irrevocably breaks out in the direction of leaving.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a turning point after which they feel it impossible to govern.
People don’t trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that it is unlikely that a prime minister will improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there for long, this postponement is over: the public service is beginning to leak; the cabinet ministers are beginning to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In one way, Brown’s position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would like to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant-in-chief.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax filings, for example, are linked to decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's misfortune -- as in the long "money for nobles" investigation of political party funding -- voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown’s situation isn’t as bad as it looks
The faults are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one has died, or been completely defrauded.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown’s, of course, always promised Stalinist tendencies: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new political donation is a good example.
The garboeske of Abraham, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not wish public recognition for his goodwill.
That may be the case, but the decision was not up to him.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew of Abraham’s agreement, but doesn’t say it’s illegal, will have to ask himself some questions, of course; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour’s main financial investor, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half of the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he diluted this determination by grasping a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - to make the measure full, of a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be drawn from" are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it is a matter for the police.
Other than that, there are other things Mr. Brown needs to do, such as finding something to be a permanent chairman for the Independent Committee on Standards in Public Life that has been unoccupied for six months, and moving forward with a comprehensive reform of political party funding.
That would require Labour hardliners to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly abandon the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a party comrade like Mr. Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve victory is through undisputed righteousness and solid competence.
