Is the credit crisis affecting America’s credit card market?
If there is blood in the water, it is only natural that back fins swirl excitedly.
Now that America’s real estate market is hurting, the predators are targeting the country’s credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion from underfunded loans spreads to other forms of consumer loans.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both depreciation and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are not recoverable or are more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it took a $1.4 billion fee levy from its American consumer finance, partly because of the weakness of credit card holders.
It is too early to panic.
Losses and losses are still low.
According to Moody, the third-quarter leaking rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in U.S. private bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to an abrupt fall of bankruptcy claims, which in turn accounted for a large part of the credit card losses; the number of registrations (and thus default fees) would rise again, whether or not the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate.
The industry also reports solid payment rates that show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
and trust in credit card-based securities is fairly strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research company, expects that the volumes of spending for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to borrow credit card debt now that home loans are drying up.
However, card issuers look at the flow of money rather than capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the creditworthiness of the borrower.
They can even be beneficial for the card issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue to pay mortgage rates drop when the real estate is worth less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the more stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
“We won’t wake up one day and completely reassess the loans,” said Gary Perlin, Capital One’s chief financial adviser.
Even if a sudden undercover crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are considerably more real.
If lower home prices and credit cuts push America into recession, industry will undoubtedly face a more grim future.
