Venus is the Earth's twin
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind turbines at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe Venus Express has provided the evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the lightning on Venus shoots at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles reports in the science magazine Nature.
According to the famous "Ursuppen-Theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there is probably hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, temperatures sometimes of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the Earth’s devil twin, but she’s a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has undertaken such a completely different development is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as no spacecraft had been on their way to exploring this planet since the early 1990s.
The latest research, now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscores the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, the researchers believe.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with the Earth are greater than initially assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud gust at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost as large with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the Sun in just under 225 days.
But he turns much slower about himself: a Venus day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly recalls the Earth, scientists assume that both planets were created under very similar conditions.
Both accumulated water that remained in oceans on Earth, but lost to space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
