These are not Warhol's boxes.
Those who combine the terms Sweden and wooden box think of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Isn't it?
Currently in Sweden, fabricated wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol’s work directory.
Most of the ninety-four "Stockholm-type" brillo boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's "Brillo-Boxes" of the year 1968, "Internal research at the Moderna Museum in Stockholm now comes to a sobering result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has made the Moderna Museum part of the art in 1995 as a gift, are well the replica of the art.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes", painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited, with Warhol's consent, hundreds of brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
They were not works of art, but their examples, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at the time were authorised as original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Typ Stockholm" rightly entered the history of art and auctions.
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has examined three privately owned brillo boxes in addition to the six museum-owned, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press chipboards were first primed and sanded, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press chipboard with a paint roller without primer - it is also not oil, but acrylic paint.
“These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol’s brillo boxes,” says Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: “If the ‘Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board’ in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will release the six boxes in its collection as a copy.”
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would pursue the “serious accusations” made regarding the soap powder boxes.
But since then, they have been shrouded in relentless silence.
